 why to ignore the Cambrian part of Britain? So, in Welsh “eng” means “space.” A space like a room somewhere? Okay, back to Saxon such word can be translated from German “eng” like “confined” or even “tight.” Thus, a “confined room”? Now, where in hell we will figure such words? Let’s keep looking into.<br /><br />And speaking in wordplay, what can be obtained from “tight”? See, the C’s have repeatedly encouraged us to play with similar sounds and letters. So, “tight” is almost “thight,” and then... “<b>thigh</b>”? Have the C’s mentioned thigh somewhere? The large bone of the hip that attaches the thigh is called <b>Ilium</b>. Ilium also is the Latin name of Troy city. See why “Iliad”? Amusing. <img src=\"/forum/styles/cass/smilies/smiley.gif\"  class=\"smilie\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\":-)\" title=\"Smile    :-)\" data-shortname=\":-)\" /><br />&#8203;</div><div style=\"text-align: center\"><script class=\"js-extraPhrases\" type=\"application/json\">{\"lightbox_close\": \"Close\",\"lightbox_next\": \"Next\",\"lightbox_previous\": \"Previous\",\"lightbox_error\": \"The requested content cannot be loaded. Please try again later.\",\"lightbox_start_slideshow\": \"Start slideshow\",\"lightbox_stop_slideshow\": \"Stop slideshow\",\"lightbox_full_screen\": \"Full screen\",\"lightbox_thumbnails\": \"Thumbnails\",\"lightbox_download\": \"Download\",\"lightbox_share\": \"Share\",\"lightbox_zoom\": \"Zoom\",\"lightbox_new_window\": \"New window\",\"lightbox_toggle_sidebar\": \"Toggle sidebar\"}</script><div class=\"bbImageWrapper  js-lbImage\" title=\"632px-Ziggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg\"data-src=\"/forum/proxy.php?image=https%3A%2F%2Fupload.wikimedia.org%2Fwikipedia%2Fcommons%2Fthumb%2Fd%2Fda%2FZiggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg%2F632px-Ziggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg&amp;hash=6820f6173c7c28f5803d83a089e0936e\" data-lb-sidebar-href=\"\" data-lb-caption-extra-html=\"\" data-single-image=\"1\"><img src=\"/forum/proxy.php?image=https%3A%2F%2Fupload.wikimedia.org%2Fwikipedia%2Fcommons%2Fthumb%2Fd%2Fda%2FZiggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg%2F632px-Ziggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg&amp;hash=6820f6173c7c28f5803d83a089e0936e\"data-url=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Ziggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg/632px-Ziggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg\"class=\"bbImage\"data-zoom-target=\"1\"style=\"width: 379px\"alt=\"632px-Ziggurat_of_UrInbound1427286134917083377.jpg\"title=\"\"width=\"\" height=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" /></div><br />&#8203;</div><div style=\"text-align: justify\">But, and if “Eng” were somebody, who could be? What sound or spelling likens to it? maybe from an ancient language? Remember, the C’s already confirmed that all languages derives from a common source. Now, some scholars have reasoned Troy at the Semitic Mesopotamia. Yet considering England or Britain, as C’s told us, how could that center the “case,” unless perhaps its mythical roots may assist the comb? Just some thoughts.&#8203;</div>","attachments":[],"reactions":[{"user_id":18002,"user":"Kaz","date":"2024-02-12T11:33:04+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":11403,"user":"Sylvia","date":"2024-02-12T04:19:26+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":18632,"user":"Bernardo GA","date":"2024-02-11T17:54:29+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":5223,"user":"happyliza","date":"2024-02-07T18:08:52+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":9839,"user":"Jo Bugman","date":"2024-02-07T02:21:11+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":17316,"user":"KaWaiAwaAwa","date":"2024-02-05T23:32:42+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":19656,"user":"JandI","date":"2024-02-05T20:09:11+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":17284,"user":"ELT","date":"2024-02-05T15:59:13+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":17945,"user":"Claus","date":"2024-02-05T14:01:35+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":13630,"user":"Stella Marys","date":"2024-02-04T16:46:07+0100","reaction":"Like"},{"user_id":7509,"user":"candasiri","date":"2024-02-04T1